Our extension for PowerShell doesn't always return the breakpoints in the response in the same order they were sent in the request e.g.:

```
    READ MESSAGE:

    {
      "type": "request",
      "seq": 19,
      "command": "setBreakpoints",
      "arguments": {
        "source": {
          "name": null,
          "path": "C:\\Users\\Keith\\.vscode-alpha\\extensions\\ms-vscode.PowerShell-0.4.1\\examples\\DebugTest.ps1",
          "sourceReference": null
        },
        "lines": [
          9,
          22
        ],
        "breakpoints": [
          {
            "line": 9,
            "condition": "$i % 10 -eq 0"
          },
          {
            "line": 22
          }
        ]
      }
    }
```

Response:

```
    WRITE MESSAGE:

    {
      "type": "response",
      "request_seq": "19",
      "command": "setBreakpoints",
      "success": true,
      "body": {
        "breakpoints": [
          {
            "verified": true,
            "message": null,
            "source": "C:\\Users\\Keith\\.vscode-alpha\\extensions\\ms-vscode.PowerShell-0.4.1\\examples\\DebugTest.ps1",
            "line": 22,
            "column": null
          },
          {
            "verified": true,
            "message": null,
            "source": "C:\\Users\\Keith\\.vscode-alpha\\extensions\\ms-vscode.PowerShell-0.4.1\\examples\\DebugTest.ps1",
            "line": 9,
            "column": null
          }
        ]
      }
    }
```

What I notice in the VSCode UI is that after I add or remove a breakpoint during a debug session, VSCode gets confused about which line my "conditional" breakpoint is on.  Check this out:
![vscodebreakpointbug](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/5177512/13402498/d063e32c-decd-11e5-861a-2c3a1e1105a0.gif)

Is there an implicit, undocumented (AFAICT) contract that says the requested breakpoints must be returned in the same order.  So far, that's the only thing I can see wrong.  

**Update**: had time to change my code to ensure the breakpoints are returned in the same order as received and this issue goes away.  Seems like that should be documented in the debug protocol - or maybe I'm looking at the wrong file - https://github.com/Microsoft/vscode/blob/master/src/vs/workbench/parts/debug/common/debugProtocol.d.ts#L495

I have the following code:

```
 getExistingThing({
        id, 
        spaceId
    }: {
        id: string, 
        spaceId: string
    }): IThingInfo {
   // Use the params object here with destructuring...
}
```

When I tried to refactor `id` to `thingId`, it renamed it correctly in the parameter object variable and the symbols in the function body, but it did not rename it in the "shape" of the parameter object (I don't know what else to call it).

Expected:

```
    getExistingThing({
        thingId,
        spaceId
    }: {
        thingId: string, <<< should change here
        spaceId: string
    }): IThingInfo {
```

Got: 

```
    getExistingThing({
        thingId, 
        spaceId
    }: {
        id: string, <<< doesn't change though
        spaceId: string
    }): IThingInfo {
```

I would also love it if someone could tell me what the various parts of this kind of function declaration is called. I use it for named arguments which I love, but I just don't know what the various pieces are called. I just know it's awesomeness.

